WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.840
Alright, welcome back. Now we'll be looking at how we can take our website we've created

00:00:07.840 --> 00:00:15.680
so far and use CSS and SCSS to further style it to your liking. So before we get going

00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:21.760
at that, we need to talk very quickly about what HTML is, because that is how all websites

00:00:21.760 --> 00:00:26.559
are created. And we need to understand how that works to be able to style the different

00:00:26.559 --> 00:00:34.240
components. So all HTML is built inside these things called divs, which are having the syntax

00:00:34.240 --> 00:00:40.799
we see right here with tridivial brackets and the name of the tag inside of it. And

00:00:40.799 --> 00:00:47.400
we can nest them like we see here as well. And a general website is built around four

00:00:47.400 --> 00:00:53.919
main tags. So we have the HTML tags, which is the outermost one that contains everything

00:00:53.919 --> 00:01:01.680
else. And inside of that, we have a head and a body. In the head, we do things like

00:01:01.680 --> 00:01:09.279
loading style sheets, loading metadata, things we don't really need for the user, and the

00:01:09.279 --> 00:01:16.480
body contains everything we see. Quarto basically deals with everything that goes into the header.

00:01:16.480 --> 00:01:21.360
And we just have to focus on what happens in the body. Some of the common HTML tags

00:01:21.360 --> 00:01:28.400
we see are these header ones, which we also use in Quarto with the pound sign. So they

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:34.559
have to go from one to six. A paragraph is what it says. We also have links, and the

00:01:34.559 --> 00:01:39.839
general div is just named div. But there's many, many more tags, but these are the most

00:01:39.839 --> 00:01:44.800
common one we will see. In addition to having a name, they can also have attributes, and

00:01:44.800 --> 00:01:50.879
they provide more information about what happens. And they all are specified the same way with

00:01:50.879 --> 00:01:57.919
a name, equal sign, and then some value in it. And this is also the same way we specify

00:01:57.919 --> 00:02:05.839
classes and IDs. So to be able to style and use a website programmatically with something

00:02:05.839 --> 00:02:12.080
like JavaScript, the different elements on the page will have different classes and IDs

00:02:12.080 --> 00:02:20.080
to be able to mark them as special in different ways. Another type of attribute is the way

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:26.880
images are being used. So we have the image tag, and it uses the source attribute to link

00:02:26.880 --> 00:02:34.880
to the file it needs to showcase. So we can style our website in two different ways. One

00:02:34.880 --> 00:02:41.199
of them is styling it inline using attributes. So here we can see we have style equal, and

00:02:41.199 --> 00:02:48.160
then we set color equal to red. This is fine, but it can be a very long, drawn-out and error-prone

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:54.479
process if you start having a more complicated website. And it is often preferred that we use

00:02:54.479 --> 00:02:59.759
a style sheet that would then be linked in the head, which is what Twitter will do for us if

00:02:59.759 --> 00:03:08.160
we specify it in the YAML file. So the way we use CSS to style these different elements on our page,

00:03:09.039 --> 00:03:17.520
we need two things. First, we need selectors, so what needs to be styled. This is telling CSS what

00:03:17.520 --> 00:03:23.199
HTML elements that need to be styled, and then the attributes, which is how they should be styled.

00:03:23.199 --> 00:03:29.119
So first, we'll talk about the selectors. So we can select something in a couple of different ways,

00:03:29.119 --> 00:03:35.679
and we can select something by a tag. So here we say, I want to select all the level one headers.

00:03:35.679 --> 00:03:41.759
We say that by saying H1, and then the curly bracket, which will inside the curly brackets,

00:03:41.759 --> 00:03:47.360
will denote how it should be styled. We can also specify something by class. That is done

00:03:47.440 --> 00:03:52.800
by putting a period before the class name. And lastly, we can talk about selecting something

00:03:52.800 --> 00:04:00.080
with an ID, and we use the pound sign before the ID name. By itself, this isn't super useful,

00:04:00.080 --> 00:04:04.720
so we need to be able to combine them in different ways. So one of the first ways of combining is

00:04:05.679 --> 00:04:15.679
doing an AND combination. So if we say H1 comma H2, then every style we apply inside these

00:04:15.679 --> 00:04:22.000
curly brackets will be applied to all of H1 headers and all of H2 headers.

00:04:23.200 --> 00:04:31.359
So a handy little thing I end up doing a lot is setting up this selector that selects all headers

00:04:31.359 --> 00:04:38.320
from level one through level six. Another selector is being able to select deeply. So if we say

00:04:39.119 --> 00:04:48.959
p space span, we are selecting all span elements that are somehow inside a p element.

00:04:48.959 --> 00:04:54.399
So here we see that here we have a span right here, but it's just a span by itself,

00:04:54.399 --> 00:05:02.480
so it doesn't do anything. But we also have a p paragraph right here, and it has a span inside.

00:05:02.559 --> 00:05:10.399
So the above selector will only select this span inside the p. A more specific one

00:05:10.399 --> 00:05:18.959
is using this greater than symbol to be able to only select one level deep. Since we can nest

00:05:18.959 --> 00:05:24.799
all these elements, there will be a hierarchy in it, and we think of things that are just inside

00:05:24.799 --> 00:05:29.839
as being one level deep, and then if you're one more level in, you're two levels deep, and so on.

00:05:29.839 --> 00:05:35.679
And a lot of websites can be very complicated with a lot of nesting, so sometimes it's useful

00:05:35.679 --> 00:05:41.359
to just say, I want to select everything that's just one level deep, and for that we use this

00:05:41.359 --> 00:05:48.239
greater than. So here we see I'm selecting happy, so we're selecting this the outermost div right

00:05:48.239 --> 00:05:58.399
here that has the class happy, and only selecting the H2 one level deep would be this first one,

00:05:58.399 --> 00:06:04.239
because the second one is two levels deep, so it wouldn't be selected. We can also do

00:06:04.239 --> 00:06:13.200
combinations, so we can say if we don't put a space between things, then we are saying and in

00:06:13.839 --> 00:06:23.200
a different way by saying all H2 elements with the class. So we can specify something jointly

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:31.600
by having the same class and a tag, and this way we can also select multiple classes in a row,

00:06:31.600 --> 00:06:36.720
because the period, we just add another period something, period something at the end. There's

00:06:36.720 --> 00:06:44.559
many more things we can do. One other type of select I want to showcase is the pseudo classes

00:06:44.559 --> 00:06:52.160
that modifies existing classes in different ways, and one you will see a lot is the hover and active

00:06:52.160 --> 00:07:00.000
one. So the hover pseudo class changes the style of something that is being hovered, so when you

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:08.079
have the mouse over it, it will apply the style we see specified in here, and active we can see that

00:07:08.079 --> 00:07:17.519
if we have a menu or a nav bar where we are on a specific page, we can say whatever page we're on

00:07:17.519 --> 00:07:24.880
right now should be styled differently than the rest. And then part of the name of CSS

00:07:25.760 --> 00:07:32.799
is the test dating, and that is a very long way of saying that if we specify multiple rules that

00:07:32.799 --> 00:07:39.200
select the same element, there is a rule set that you can find online if you search for it

00:07:39.200 --> 00:07:45.279
that specifies who wins. It's quite complicated, but the general rule is that a more specific

00:07:46.079 --> 00:07:54.880
selection wins to a less specific selection. So if you have a rule for h1 and a rule for h1

00:07:55.760 --> 00:08:03.839
title class, the h1 title class will win because it uses a tag and a class which is more specific

00:08:03.839 --> 00:08:08.880
than just a tag. Now that we've found out how to select different classes, we can also look at

00:08:08.880 --> 00:08:15.119
how we can change things, and we can change things by how they look or how they're positioned

00:08:15.119 --> 00:08:21.279
from each other. And things how look is things like color sizes, and colors can both be text

00:08:21.279 --> 00:08:28.480
color, border color, background color, all different things. So the general layout model

00:08:28.480 --> 00:08:37.119
we use in HTML is that each element on a page has a content area here you see in blue,

00:08:37.119 --> 00:08:43.359
and then it has a border. So border goes all the way around it. A lot of the times it's invisible,

00:08:43.359 --> 00:08:51.119
but it's still there. Then there's a padding, which is the spacing from the border to the content.

00:08:51.119 --> 00:08:58.479
So it's like the inside spacing, and we have the margin, which is the outside spacing as well.

00:08:58.479 --> 00:09:04.159
The content is specified using length or percentages, and there's many, many different

00:09:04.159 --> 00:09:12.640
ways of specifying length in CSS. So we can either specify by pixels or by any other unit we have,

00:09:12.640 --> 00:09:16.719
or we can do things like percentages whenever it makes sense. So sometimes we can say,

00:09:17.599 --> 00:09:24.159
I want the width to be 50% of the width, and it will take up half of its parent's width.

00:09:24.159 --> 00:09:32.159
Padding, which is the spacing between the content and its border, can be specified in two different

00:09:32.159 --> 00:09:40.000
ways. So we can either specify it once using the padding attribute or specifying with the four

00:09:40.559 --> 00:09:47.440
more specific attributes, which is padding, bottom, left, right, and top. These are also lengths and

00:09:47.440 --> 00:09:53.359
percentages. It works in a couple different ways, but the main thing is if you want all

00:09:54.000 --> 00:10:01.119
the four values to be the same, we can use padding as the value here, and it just works all the way out.

00:10:02.400 --> 00:10:07.440
And if you want to be more specific, we can specify the four values independently. The border

00:10:07.440 --> 00:10:13.760
works in pretty much the same way, but instead of having top, bottom, left, and right, it has

00:10:13.760 --> 00:10:20.400
color, style, and width. So we can specify them at once, or we can specify them one at a time.

00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:28.880
And margin works just as padding did. Now that we saw what CSS is, you might be wondering why we're

00:10:28.880 --> 00:10:37.200
also been talking about SCSS. So SCSS, I find very useful because it's an extension of CSS.

00:10:37.200 --> 00:10:45.039
It's very useful for the types of websites that we end up creating when we work with Toro. And

00:10:45.039 --> 00:10:52.239
Toro have native support with SCSS. So why do we use it? The first and main reason is it's CSS

00:10:52.239 --> 00:10:59.280
compatible. So just because you have a SAS file in your product doesn't mean you actually need to

00:10:59.280 --> 00:11:05.280
use it. You can just use plain CSS, which we actually will be seeing more of later. But it

00:11:05.280 --> 00:11:12.799
has a lot of features that just elevate our day-to-day use with CSS quite a lot. And it's

00:11:12.799 --> 00:11:18.559
quite mature, so there's very few breaking changes over time. It's a fairly stable product. And you

00:11:18.559 --> 00:11:26.559
can kind of think of it as CSS, but with variables, nested rules, and functions. The way it works is

00:11:26.559 --> 00:11:34.400
you have your SCSS file, and it will compile and generate a CSS file, which a browser will understand.

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:42.080
So when you push up your website, you don't actually push up the SCSS file. It will be a

00:11:42.080 --> 00:11:47.679
generated file. But Toro will do all of this for you, so you don't have to worry about it. So we have

00:11:47.679 --> 00:11:55.119
things like SAS variables. So much like we have in Python, we're able to store value in a variable

00:11:55.119 --> 00:12:01.760
and then use it later. And this is very nice to be able to reduce repetition. And the syntax is

00:12:01.760 --> 00:12:09.359
dollar sign, variable name, and then colon, and then what value we want. I end up using it a lot for

00:12:09.359 --> 00:12:14.880
colors, so we can specify our color theme at the beginning and then use it throughout. We also have

00:12:14.880 --> 00:12:20.960
the idea of nested rules. If you have a website where you need to style a lot of things, you end up

00:12:20.960 --> 00:12:27.119
writing quite a lot of different rules to specify different things, but some of them are connected

00:12:27.119 --> 00:12:35.520
by what they do. So here we have like the h1 or h2 header, and we want to have a specific color,

00:12:35.520 --> 00:12:42.479
but we want any links inside of it to have a different color. So we could specify it on the

00:12:42.479 --> 00:12:49.440
right by two different rules, but we could also specify it on the left, which is the CSS nested

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:58.000
rules. So anytime you specify something inside another thing, it knows that it uses both.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:02.239
For this example, it isn't a lot, but it ends up becoming very useful long-term,

00:13:03.200 --> 00:13:10.719
because it forces you to keep things that are related close to each other in the code. And it

00:13:10.719 --> 00:13:16.880
also works with the selectors combination. So you can also say here we use the greater than symbol

00:13:17.520 --> 00:13:24.479
inside our nested rule, and it just works. And it just adds a native organization. So here I have

00:13:24.479 --> 00:13:32.640
a speech class I created for a different project, and it uses nested rules. And it means that every

00:13:32.640 --> 00:13:40.960
single thing right here, I know that since it's inside this speech class, I know they're all

00:13:40.960 --> 00:13:47.359
related. And the IDE I'm using knows that they're all related, and I can collapse and

00:13:48.640 --> 00:13:53.039
work around with it in a very pleasing way. There's also the idea of midsings.

00:13:54.239 --> 00:14:00.239
And that's another way of reducing repetition. So we know that we need to apply the same

00:14:00.320 --> 00:14:07.919
attributes to a lot of different selectors. We could use the idea of a midsing. So we

00:14:07.919 --> 00:14:14.960
specify midsing. Here I told padding small. And we can include it under a lot of different

00:14:15.760 --> 00:14:23.200
selectors. And it essentially just copy pastes the values in. And you see,

00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:31.280
and this is not like a make it or break it feature. But what it does is, once you see

00:14:31.280 --> 00:14:36.400
attributes for it, you really love it. Oh, this makes perfect sense. I'm going to use it right

00:14:36.400 --> 00:14:41.359
here, save a little bit of real estate. And we also have functions. So there's a lot of

00:14:41.359 --> 00:14:48.239
functions to talk about. The main ones I end up using is the color modification functions.

00:14:48.719 --> 00:14:55.599
So we tend to darken a color or lighten a color. But there's also much more expansive,

00:14:55.599 --> 00:15:01.679
you can do math, there's a conditional logic you can use in this. Plus it all compiles before

00:15:01.679 --> 00:15:07.280
it goes up on the website. But here is an example that I use a lot where I specify a few number of

00:15:07.280 --> 00:15:14.479
colors at the beginning. And then I can slightly modify them. So I have different colors of blue,

00:15:15.440 --> 00:15:21.039
but they're all derivatives of our main one color. And if we decide this color isn't actually

00:15:21.599 --> 00:15:26.719
modified a little bit, all the changes propagate through the entire style sheet.

00:15:26.719 --> 00:15:32.159
All right, so we learned about how to actually make the styling happening. But we also need

00:15:32.159 --> 00:15:38.479
to think about the content on the slides and the different websites we have. And a very important

00:15:38.479 --> 00:15:43.840
thing is to have a consistent design. So the way most people work when they look at a thing,

00:15:44.479 --> 00:15:50.640
we see and look for similarities and differences whenever we see a page or something else,

00:15:50.640 --> 00:15:57.359
and we'll pick up when something is different. You will assign value on differently styled elements.

00:15:57.359 --> 00:16:04.719
And we can use this for good or for bad. So if we're very conscious about how we style everything,

00:16:04.719 --> 00:16:09.359
we can direct the user's attention to the parts of the website we want them to

00:16:10.159 --> 00:16:15.440
take their attention to. But if we have passively styled the website, we might

00:16:15.440 --> 00:16:21.280
accidentally draw attention to a section that didn't need to be drawn attention to.

00:16:22.559 --> 00:16:30.000
If you follow the CSS paradigm of the way we style things, this won't be an issue as much,

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:37.119
because the styling pretty much just happens all the way around. We can choose colors. There's

00:16:37.599 --> 00:16:44.559
three main places you can do it. You can either be forced into a color scheme that will use some

00:16:44.559 --> 00:16:50.880
guidelines you can find. And that's just finding it in your internal documentations and pull out

00:16:50.880 --> 00:16:57.919
the colors you try to use. You can pick them yourself. And a thing I'll end up doing is on

00:16:57.919 --> 00:17:03.760
Pinterest and search something, something color palette. And there's a lot of different

00:17:04.319 --> 00:17:09.920
inspiration online. Once we've selected the color we want, I like to create a color palette.

00:17:11.119 --> 00:17:17.680
So the way I create it is I do it as a set of variables, and all the variables are prefetched

00:17:17.680 --> 00:17:24.800
with theme dash. This way I know what they are when I use them, and I give them very human

00:17:24.800 --> 00:17:32.400
readable names. So it might be a very specific shade of blue, but I just hold it blue.

00:17:33.119 --> 00:17:37.520
And if there's multiple blues, you need a light blue, and a blue, and a dark blue,

00:17:37.520 --> 00:17:42.479
or something like that. But you shouldn't be too specific, because it's the general idea of blue

00:17:42.479 --> 00:17:47.680
you're using here. And then we can use it throughout with the light and dark function

00:17:47.680 --> 00:17:54.640
if we need some slight variations of it. And then the way we choose fonts is to keep

00:17:55.439 --> 00:18:00.000
accessibility in mind, and maybe the readable font. There's a lot of very fun,

00:18:00.959 --> 00:18:10.400
handwritten fonts that might look really nice on a wedding invitation or other artistic purposes,

00:18:11.359 --> 00:18:24.160
but wouldn't be good for general text in our website. And it's not as exciting of an advice,

00:18:24.160 --> 00:18:30.000
but commonly used fonts are by definition readable, because they're familiar.

00:18:31.520 --> 00:18:36.719
So using a font that everybody uses gives you the benefit that people are used to it.

00:18:36.719 --> 00:18:41.520
But you also need to take into account that some fonts are designed to be used in different places.

00:18:41.520 --> 00:18:47.280
So fonts that might work really well on print might not work as well on the web, or

00:18:47.839 --> 00:18:53.199
very old. There are some old fonts that were designed for typewriters, because of the way

00:18:53.199 --> 00:19:02.160
typewriters worked, but are solving for problems that we don't have anymore in our digital media.

00:19:03.359 --> 00:19:08.400
And then another sad advice is to don't pick too many. Because if you start picking too many fonts

00:19:08.400 --> 00:19:16.560
for a project, it starts taking away or tries to indicate importance on the website. So pick a

00:19:16.560 --> 00:19:21.920
couple of colors. You generally want a header font, a normal text font, and a quote font.

00:19:21.920 --> 00:19:27.599
And you can maybe do one more, but you want to keep it at a very reasonable amount.

00:19:29.760 --> 00:19:36.079
And then lastly, we want to make sure we maintain accessibility. The long and short of it is you

00:19:36.079 --> 00:19:42.400
want your website to be seen by people. So it's against your best interests to make it so some

00:19:42.479 --> 00:19:50.000
subset of the population have a hard time accessing your website. And this can be

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:56.719
via disability or other impairment, but you should want it to be visible to as many people as

00:19:56.719 --> 00:20:02.000
possible. Other types of things we can do, we can avoid blinking and flashing content, because

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:08.719
you most likely don't need it. You can maintain high color contrast. Right here, we have

00:20:08.719 --> 00:20:14.319
dark text on a white background. If we make the text lighter, at one point, it becomes really

00:20:14.319 --> 00:20:22.160
hard to see. We can add all text to non-text elements, such as pictures or drafts, to make

00:20:22.160 --> 00:20:27.839
sure that people on screen readers can see them as well. Another thing we can do is ensure

00:20:28.800 --> 00:20:36.000
auto-complete functionality via the keyboard. So if you do, I want to say it's there. So on my

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:46.719
Mac, I can do Option-Tab, and it will go through the links on this website right here. So it first

00:20:46.719 --> 00:20:52.000
goes to the first link, and if you do one more time, it goes to the hamburger menu at the bottom left.

00:20:53.599 --> 00:21:01.040
So if you go here and click Enter, you can navigate the website without ever

00:21:01.760 --> 00:21:07.119
using the mouse. So that's another accessibility. And this likely also showed us

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:13.280
one of my favorite color contrast chapters. So we can see right here,

00:21:13.920 --> 00:21:17.920
we have a background color and a foreground color. If I change

00:21:20.959 --> 00:21:29.359
the background color, move the saturation down, and we see a number. So

00:21:29.439 --> 00:21:33.599
when the number is high, we have a bit contrast. When the number goes down, we have lower contrast.

00:21:34.880 --> 00:21:41.839
And as we move the lighting down, we get some small numbers, and we see on the right-hand side

00:21:42.560 --> 00:21:51.359
that some of these values fail. So we see here, we can pass them all just when we hit seven.

00:21:52.160 --> 00:21:59.040
So the color contrast we need to ensure accessibility will depend on the size of the

00:21:59.040 --> 00:22:06.880
text. So large text can manage a low contrast, where small text need a bit contrast. But in

00:22:06.880 --> 00:22:12.400
general, you should make this as high as possible without messing with your overall design.

00:22:12.400 --> 00:22:16.880
All right, now we're back at the website we've been working on so far, and we're going to try

00:22:16.880 --> 00:22:23.119
to apply what we learned to our style sheet. So here we have the Toro.yml file that has everything

00:22:23.119 --> 00:22:32.079
we need, and we also have our styles.css file. So before we move on, we noted that we have some

00:22:32.079 --> 00:22:37.680
styling happening down here below. So we specified some things directly in the HTML,

00:22:38.479 --> 00:22:44.160
and we're going to try to undo some of those. So I'm going to take away

00:22:46.959 --> 00:22:50.959
this line right here, and it will undo some of the styling we saw.

00:22:52.400 --> 00:22:57.680
And I'm going to re-implement it right in here. So I'm going to just paste them in here so we can

00:22:57.680 --> 00:23:05.760
see them. And I want to use the technique I showed earlier about creating a color palette.

00:23:07.520 --> 00:23:15.040
So at the beginning, I will create this color palette by using the theme-naming convention.

00:23:15.040 --> 00:23:22.000
So I'm reusing the light green, green, and black that we saw down here, and now we need to apply

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:28.880
them. So we already have the sass variable set up right here under colors. We just need to use them.

00:23:28.880 --> 00:23:37.359
So the body background right here, this theme light green, this is partly why we use the names

00:23:37.359 --> 00:23:44.319
because auto-completion works really well. The body color was theme green,

